subjectivity to an alternative "plantlike" one that emphasizes interdependence, vulnerability, and metamorphosis.While providing the necessary historical context, the book also addresses a question that has been very important for recent feminist theory, especially French feminism, namely, the question of the possible configuration of a feminine subject. The idea of the "vegetative" subject takes the traditional alignment of the feminine with nature and the earth and subverts and transforms it into a positive possibility. Although the roots of this alternative conception of subjectivity can be found in Kant's third Critique and its legacy in nineteenth-century Naturphilosophie, the work of Luce Irigaray brings it to fruition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBotanyxHistoryx18th centuryxGermany. 0aBotanyxHistoryx19th centuryxGermany. 0aBotanyzGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 0aBotanyzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aFeminist theory. 0aPhilosophy of naturexHistoryx18th centuryxGermany. 0aPhilosophy of naturexHistoryx19th centuryxGermany. 0aPhilosophy of naturezGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 0aPhilosophy of naturezGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aSubjectivityxGermany. 0aSubjectivity. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791488522423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791488522/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles